<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The aggregate market value of the voting stock held by non-affiliates
of the Registrant, (based on the closing price of such stock ($27.01 per
share), as reported on the New York Stock Exchange, on June 30, 2003) was
approximately $448,600,000 (for purposes of this calculation, directors and
executive officers are treated as affiliates).</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The number of shares of the Registrant&#146;s common stock outstanding as of February 29, 2004, was 20,086,319
shares, of which approximately 1,333,541 were held by affiliates.</FONT></P>

Annual Meeting of Shareholders (to be filed pursuant to Regulation 14A) is
incorporated by reference into Part III of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A001"></A>PART I</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A002"></A>ITEM 1.&#160; BUSINESS</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>WEBSITE ACCESS OF REGISTRANT&#146;S REPORTS</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">A
copy of this Annual Report on Form 10-K, along with the Company&#146;s Quarterly
Reports on Form 10-Q, Current Reports on Form 8-K and any amendments to the
aforementioned filings, are available on the Company&#146;s website free of charge.
The filings can be found on the Investors&#146; page under SEC Filings.&#160; The Company&#146;s website also contains its
Corporate Governance Guidelines, Code of Ethics Policy and the charters of the
committees of the Board of Directors. These items can be found on the
Investors&#146; page under Corporate Governance. The Company&#146;s website address is
www.maac.net.&#160; Reference to the
Company&#146;s website does not constitute incorporation by reference of the
information contained on the site and should not be considered part of this
document. All of the aforementioned materials may also be obtained free of
charge by contacting the Investor Relations Department at Mid-America Apartment
Communities, Inc., 6584 Poplar Avenue, Suite 300, Memphis, TN 38138.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>OVERVIEW OF THE COMPANY</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Founded in 1994,
Mid-America Apartment Communities, Inc. (the &#147;Company&#148;) is a Memphis, Tennessee-based
self-administered and self-managed umbrella partnership real estate investment
trust (&#147;REIT&#148;) that focuses on acquiring, owning and operating apartment
communities.&#160; Between 1994 and December
31, 2003, the Company increased the number of properties of which it is the
sole owner from 22 to 124 properties with 34,686 apartment units, representing
an increase of 29,106 apartment units.&#160;
The Company is also a participant in a joint venture with Crow Holdings,
Mid-America CH/Realty LP (&#147;CH/Realty&#148;).&#160;
CH/Realty owned three properties with 1,048 apartment units at December
31, 2003.&#160; The Company retains a 33.33%
ownership interest in the joint venture and is paid a management fee of 4% of
revenues from the apartment communities owned by the joint venture.&#160; &#160;</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s business is
conducted principally through Mid-America Apartments, L.P. (the &#147;Operating
Partnership&#148;).&#160; The Company is the sole
general partner of the Operating Partnership, holding 201,502 common units of
partnership interest (&#147;Common Units&#148;) comprising a 1% general partnership
interest in the Operating Partnership as of December 31, 2003.&#160; The Company&#146;s wholly-owned qualified REIT
subsidiary, MAC II of Delaware, Inc., a Delaware corporation, is a limited
partner in the Operating Partnership and, as of December 31, 2003, held
17,010,015 Common Units, or 84.42% of all outstanding Common Units.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company employed
1,069 full time and 82 part time employees at December 31, 2003.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>OPERATING PHILOSOPHY</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s primary
objective is to maintain a stable cash flow that will fund its dividend through
all parts of the real estate investment cycle.&#160;
The Company focuses on growing through its existing investments and,
when accretive to cash flow and shareholder value, through external
investments.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>INVESTMENT
FOCUS</I>.&#160; The Company&#146;s
primary investment focus is on apartment communities in the Southeastern United
States and Texas.&#160; Between 1994 and
1997, the Company grew largely through the acquisition and redevelopment of
existing communities.&#160; Between 1998 and
2000, its concentration was on development of new communities.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">2</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">The
Company&#146;s present  focus is on the acquisition of properties that it believes can be
repositioned  with appropriate use of capital and its operating management skills. The
Company is also interested in increasing its investment in properties in larger  and
faster growing markets within its current market area to balance its  portfolio between
small, middle and large-tier markets, and intends to do this  through acquiring apartment
communities with the potential for above average  growth and return through investments
in joint ventures and in direct  purchases. The Company will continue its established
process of selling mature  assets, and will adapt its investment focus to opportunities
and markets.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>HIGH
QUALITY ASSETS</I>.&#160; The
Company maintains its assets in excellent condition, believing that continuous
maintenance will lead to higher long-run returns on investment.&#160; It believes that being recognized by civic
and industry trade organizations for the high quality of its properties,
landscaping, and property management will lead to higher rents and
profitability.&#160; The Company periodically
sells assets selectively in order to ensure that its portfolio consists only of
high quality, well-located assets within its market area.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>DIVERSIFIED MARKET FOCUS</I>.&#160; The Company believes the stability of its
cash flow is enhanced and it will generate higher risk adjusted cash flow
returns with lower volatility through its diversified investments over large,
middle and small-tier markets throughout the southeastern United States and
Texas. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>INTENSIVE MANAGEMENT FOCUS</I>.&#160; The Company strongly emphasizes on-site
property management. Particular attention is paid to opportunities to increase
rents, raise average occupancy rates, and control costs.&#160; Property managers and regional managers are
given the responsibility for monitoring market trends and the discretion to
react to such trends.&#160; The Company, as
part of its intense management focus, has established a number of training
programs to produce highly competent property managers, leasing consultants and
service technicians who work on-site at the Company&#146;s apartment communities
(the &#147;Communities&#148;) to generate the highest possible income from the Company&#146;s
assets. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>DECENTRALIZED OPERATIONAL STRUCTURE</I>.&#160; The Company operates in a decentralized
manner.&#160; Management believes that its
decentralized operating structure capitalizes on specific market knowledge,
provides greater personal accountability than a centralized structure and is
beneficial in the acquisition, redevelopment and development processes.&#160; To support this decentralized operational
structure, senior and executive management are proactively involved in
supporting and reviewing property operations through extensive asset management
programs and frequent on-site visitations. The Company is currently in the
process of installing a new web-based property management system which
increases the amount of information shared between senior and executive
management and the properties, and does so on a real time basis, improving the
support provided to the operating environment.&#160;
</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>PROACTIVE&#160; BALANCE
SHEET AND PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company focuses on
maximizing the return on assets and adding to the intrinsic underlying value of
each share of the Company&#146;s common stock, routinely reviewing each asset based
on its determined value and selling those which no longer fit its investment
criteria.&#160; The Company constantly
evaluates the effectiveness of its capital allocations and makes adjustments to
its strategy, including investing in existing and new apartment communities,
debt retirement, and repurchases or issuances of shares of the Company&#146;s
preferred and common stock.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">3</FONT></P>


<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>STRATEGIES</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company seeks to
increase operating cash flow and earnings per share to maximize shareholder
value through a balanced strategy of internal and external growth.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>OPERATING GROWTH STRATEGY</I>.&#160; Management&#146;s goal is to maximize the
Company&#146;s return on investment in each Community by increasing rental rates and
reducing operating expenses while maintaining high occupancy levels.&#160; The Company seeks higher net rental revenues
by enhancing and maintaining the competitiveness of the Communities and
managing expenses through its system of detailed management reporting and
accountability in order to achieve increases in operating cash flow.&#160; The steps taken to meet these objectives
include: </FONT></P>
<TABLE ALIGN=CENTER  BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH="100%">
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&#149;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">empowering the Company&#146;s property managers to adjust
  rents in response to local market conditions and to concentrate resident
  turnover during peak rental demand months;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&#149;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">offering new services to residents, including
  telephone, cable, and internet access, on which the Company generates fee and
  commission income;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>

  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">implementing programs to control expenses through
  investment in cost-saving initiatives, such as the installation of individual
  apartment unit water and utility meters in certain Communities;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>

  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&#149;</FONT></P></TD>

  to identify best practices and improvement areas;</FONT></P></TD>

  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>

  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>

  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">improving the &#147;curb appeal&#148; of the Communities
  through extensive landscaping and exterior improvements and repositioning
  Communities from time to time to maintain market leadership positions;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>

  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&#149;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">compensating employees through performance-based
  compensation and stock ownership programs; </FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&#149;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">maintaining a hands-on management style and &#147;flat&#148;
  organizational structure that emphasizes senior management&#146;s continued close
  contact with the market and employees; </FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>

  <TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN=TOP>

  <TD WIDTH="95%" VALIGN=TOP>
  <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">developing new ancillary income programs aimed at
  delivering new consumer services and products to its residents while
  generating fee income for the Company.</FONT></P></TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>JOINT VENTURE STRATEGY</I>.&#160; One of the Company&#146;s strategies is to
co-invest with private capital partners in joint venture opportunities which
enable it to obtain a higher return on its investment through management fees,
which leverages the Company&#146;s recognized skills in acquiring, repositioning,
redeveloping and managing multifamily investments. In addition, the joint
venture investment strategy provides a platform for creating more capital
diversification and lower investment risk for the Company. The Company is
actively seeking attractively priced opportunities in which it and its joint
venture partner</FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">4</FONT></P>


<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">can  invest.&#160; The
Company established a joint  venture in 2002 with Crow Holdings and established a second
joint venture with  Crow Holdings in early 2004.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>DISPOSITION STRATEGY</I>.&#160; The Company is committed to the selective
disposition of mature assets, defined as those apartment communities that no
longer meet the Company&#146;s investment criteria and long-term strategic
objectives.&#160; Typically, the Company
selects assets for disposition that do not meet its present investment criteria
including future return on investment, location, market, potential for growth,
and capital needs. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On July 10, 2003, the
Company sold the Crossings apartments, an 80-unit apartment community in
Memphis, Tennessee, that was built in 1973. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>ACQUISITION STRATEGY</I>.&#160; One of the Company&#146;s growth strategies is to
acquire and redevelop apartment communities that meet its investment criteria
and focus as discussed above. The Company has extensive experience and
research-based skills in the acquisition and repositioning of multifamily
properties. In addition, the Company will acquire newly built and developed
properties that can be purchased on a favorable pricing basis. The Company will continue to evaluate
opportunities that arise, and will utilize this strategy to increase the share
of its assets in faster growing and larger markets in the Southeast and Texas.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On January 20, 2003,
CH/Realty acquired The Preserve at Arbor Lakes, a 284-unit apartment community
in Jacksonville, Florida.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On February 7, 2003, the
Company acquired the Green Oaks apartments, a 300-unit apartment community
located in Grand Prairie, Texas.&#160; On May
1, 2003 the Company transferred the Green Oaks apartments to CH/Realty.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On May 6, 2003, the
Company acquired the Jefferson Pines apartments, a 308-unit apartment community
located in Houston, Texas.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On August 25, 2003, the
Company purchased the limited partnership interest held by Blackstone Real
Estate Advisors (&#147;Blackstone&#148;) in BRE/MAAC Associates, LLC (&#147;BreMaac&#148;), a joint
venture between the Company and Blackstone which owned 10 properties containing
2,793 apartment units. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On September 30, 2003,
the Company acquired Los Rios Park apartments, a 498-unit community located in
Plano, Texas.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On December 3, 2003, the
Company acquired the Lighthouse Court apartments, a 501-unit community located
in Jacksonville, Florida.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>DEVELOPMENT STRATEGY</I>.&#160; In late 1997, the Company&#146;s emphasis shifted
from acquisitions to development because of its belief that under then-current
market conditions, such development would generate higher quality assets and
higher long-term investment returns.&#160; In
2002, the Company completed a $300 million construction program of high quality
apartments in several markets.&#160; This
represents the completion of the development program initiated in 1997.&#160; In 1999, management decided to exit the
construction and development business upon completion of the Company&#146;s existing
development pipeline after determining that market conditions were changing,
making it unlikely that future proposed projects would meet the Company&#146;s
profitability targets over the next few years.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">5</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">As  of December
31, 2003, the Company had no properties in development.&#160; The Company periodically
evaluates  opportunities for profitable future development investments.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>COMMON
AND PREFERRED STOCK.</I>&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company continuously
reviews opportunities for lowering its cost of capital, and increasing value
per share. The Company evaluates opportunities to repurchase stock when it
believes that its stock price is below the value of its assets and accordingly
repurchased common stock, funded by asset sales, between 1999 and 2001. The
Company also looks for opportunities where it can acquire or develop
communities, selectively funded by stock sales, when it will add to shareholder
value and the investment return is projected to substantially exceed its cost
of capital. The Company also opportunistically seeks to lower its cost of
capital through refinancing preferred stock and debt such as it did in 2003.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On July 10, 2003, in an underwritten public
offering, the Company sold 5,600,000 shares of its 8.30% Series H Cumulative
Redeemable Preferred Stock (&#147;Series H&#148;) at $25 per share less an underwriting
discount of $0.7875 per share.&#160; The net
proceeds of the sale were applied to the redemption of all the issued and
outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s 9.5% Series A Cumulative Preferred Stock
and 9 3/8% Series C Cumulative Redeemable Preferred Stock as well as 1,600,000
shares of the 1,938,830 issued and outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s 8 7/8%
Series B Cumulative Preferred Stock (&#147;Series B&#148;) on August 12, 2003.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On July 16, 2003, the underwriters of the Company&#146;s
Series H offering exercised an option to purchase an additional 525,000 shares
of the Series H preferred stock for $25 per share less the underwriting
discount, and on August 4, 2003, the underwriters exercised an option to
purchase the remaining additional 75,000 shares of the Series H preferred stock
for $25 per share less the underwriting discount.&#160; The net proceeds were used to redeem the remaining issued and
outstanding shares of the Series B preferred stock on August 18, 2003.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On August 22, 2003, the Company sold 700,000 shares
of its common stock to certain advisory clients of Cohen &amp; Steers Capital
Management, Inc. The stock was sold at a price of $28.40 per share. The
$19,870,000 in net proceeds from the sale were used to partially fund the purchase
of the BreMaac limited partnership interest held by Blackstone.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On September 19, 2003, the Company sold 665,000
shares of its common stock to certain advisory clients of Cohen &amp; Steers
Capital Management, Inc. and to Scudder RREEF Real Estate Fund II, Inc. The
stock was sold at a price of $29.36 per share. The $19,500,000 in net proceeds
from the sale were used to partially fund the purchase the Los Rios Park
apartments.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On December 2, 2003, the Company sold 400,000
shares of its common stock to RREEF America, L.L.C. on behalf of itself and
Scudder RREEF Real Estate Fund II, Inc. The stock was sold at a price of $30.00
per share. The $11,996,000 in net proceeds from the sale were used to partially
fund the acquisition of the Lighthouse Court apartments.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>SHARE REPURCHASE PROGRAM</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In 1999, the Company&#146;s
Board of Directors approved an increase in the number of shares of the
Company&#146;s common stock authorized to be repurchased to 4 million shares.&#160; As of December 31, 2003 the Company had
repurchased a total of approximately 1.86 million shares (8% of the shares of
common stock and Common Units outstanding as of the beginning of the repurchase
program).&#160; From time to time the Company
intends to sell assets based on its disposition strategy outlined in this
Annual Report and </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">6</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">use  the
proceeds to repurchase shares when it believes that shareholder value is  enhanced.&#160; Factors
affecting this  determination include the share price, asset dispositions and pricing,
financing agreements and rates of return of alternative investments.&#160; No shares were
repurchased during 2002 or  2003 under this plan.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>COMPETITION</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">All of the Company&#146;s
Communities are located in areas that include other apartment communities.&#160; Occupancy and rental rates are affected by
the number of competitive apartment communities in a particular area.&#160; The owners of competing apartment
communities may have greater resources than the Company, and the managers of
these communities may have more experience than the Company&#146;s management.&#160; Moreover, single-family rental housing,
manufactured housing, condominiums and the new and existing home markets
provide housing alternatives to potential residents of apartment communities.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Apartment
communities compete on the basis of monthly rent, discounts, and facilities
offered such as apartment size and amenities, and apartment community
amenities, including recreational facilities, resident services, and physical
property condition.&#160; The Company makes
capital improvements to both the Communities and individual apartments on a
regular basis in order to maintain a competitive position in each individual
market.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>ENVIRONMENTAL
MATTERS</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">As
part of the acquisition process, the Company generally obtains environmental
studies on all of its Communities from various outside environmental
engineering firms.&#160; The purpose of these
studies is to identify potential sources of contamination at the Communities
and to assess the status of environmental regulatory compliance.&#160; These studies generally include historical
reviews of the Communities, reviews of certain public records, preliminary
investigations of the sites and surrounding properties, visual inspection for
the presence of asbestos, PCBs and underground storage tanks and the
preparation and issuance of written reports.&#160;
Depending on the results of these studies, more invasive procedures,
such as soil sampling or ground water analysis, will be performed to
investigate potential sources of contamination.&#160; These studies must be satisfactorily completed before the Company
takes ownership of an acquisition property, however, no assurance can be given
that the studies identify all significant environmental problems.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Under
various federal, state and local laws and regulations, an owner or operator of
real estate may be liable for the costs of removal or remediation of certain
hazardous or toxic substances on properties.&#160;
Such laws often impose such liability without regard to whether the
owner caused or knew of the presence of hazardous or toxic substances and
whether or not the storage of such substances was in violation of a resident&#146;s
lease.&#160; Furthermore, the cost of
remediation and removal of such substances may be substantial, and the presence
of such substances, or the failure to promptly remediate such substances, may
adversely affect the owner&#146;s ability to sell such real estate or to borrow
using such real estate as collateral.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
Company is aware of environmental concerns specifically relating to potential
issues resulting from mold in residential properties and has in place an active
management and preventive maintenance program that includes procedures
specifically related to mold.&#160; The
Company has established a policy requiring residents to sign a mold addendum to
lease.&#160; The Company has also purchased a
$2 million insurance policy that covers remediation and exposure to mold.&#160; The current policy expires in 2007, but is
renewable at that time. The Company, therefore, believes that its exposure to
this issue is limited and controlled.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">7</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
environmental studies received by the Company have not revealed any material
environmental liabilities.&#160; The Company
is not aware of any existing conditions that would currently be considered an
environmental liability.&#160; Nevertheless,
it is possible that the studies do not reveal all environmental liabilities or
that there are material environmental liabilities of which the Company is
unaware.&#160; Moreover, no assurance can be
given concerning future laws, ordinances or regulations, or the potential introduction
of hazardous or toxic substances by neighboring properties or residents. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
Company believes that its Communities are in compliance in all material
respects with all applicable federal, state and local ordinances and
regulations regarding hazardous or toxic substances and other environmental
matters.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>RECENT DEVELOPMENTS</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>DISTRIBUTION</I>.&#160; In January 2004, the Company announced a
quarterly distribution to common shareholders of $.585 per share, paid on
January 31, 2004.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>ACQUISITIONS.</I>&#160; On January 15, 2004, the Company established
a second joint venture with Crow Holdings, Mid-America CH/Realty II LP
(&#147;CH/Realty II&#148;) which acquired the Jefferson at Timberglen apartments, a
522-unit community in Dallas, Texas.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On January 23, 2004, the
Company acquired the Monthaven Park Apartments, a 456-unit community located in
Hendersonville, Tennessee.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A003"></A>ITEM 2.&#160; PROPERTIES</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company and its joint
venture seek to acquire apartment communities located in the southeastern
United States and Texas that are primarily appealing to middle income residents
with the potential for above average growth and return on investment.&#160; Approximately 75% of the Company&#146;s apartment
units are located in Georgia, Florida, Tennessee and Texas markets. The
Company&#146;s strategic focus is to provide its residents high quality apartment
units in attractive community settings, characterized by extensive landscaping
and attention to aesthetic detail. The Company utilizes its experience and
expertise in maintenance, landscaping, marketing and management to effectively
&#147;reposition&#148; many of the apartment communities it acquires to raise occupancy
levels and per unit average rents.&#160; </FONT></P>

1,048 apartment units owned by the Company&#146;s joint venture, at December 31,
2003:</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2"><B><B><A NAME="A004"></A>ITEM
3.&#160; LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</B></B></FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company is not
presently subject to any material litigation nor, to the Company&#146;s knowledge,
is any material litigation threatened against the Company, other than routine
litigation arising in the ordinary course of business, some of which is
expected to be covered by liability insurance and none of which is expected to
have a material adverse effect on the business, financial condition, liquidity
or results of operations of the Company.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A005"></A>ITEM 4.&#160; SUBMISSION OF
MATTERS TO A VOTE OF SECURITY HOLDERS</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">None.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A006"></A>PART II</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A007"></A>ITEM 5.&#160; MARKET FOR
REGISTRANT&#146;S COMMON EQUITY AND RELATED STOCKHOLDER MATTERS</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s common
stock has been listed and traded on the New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) under
the symbol &#147;MAA&#148; since its initial public offering in February 1994.&#160; On February 27, 2004, the reported last sale
price of the Company&#146;s common stock on the NYSE was $35.86 per share, and there
were approximately 1,500 holders of record of the common stock.&#160; The Company estimates there are
approximately 13,900 beneficial owners of its common stock.&#160; The following table sets forth the quarterly
high and low sales prices of the Company&#146;s common stock as reported on the NYSE
and the dividends declared by the Company with respect to the periods
indicated.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s quarterly
dividend rate is currently $0.585 per common share.&#160; The Board of Directors reviews and declares the dividend rate
quarterly.&#160; Actual dividends made by the
Company will be affected by a number of factors, including the gross revenues
received from the Communities, the operating expenses of the Company, the
interest expense incurred on borrowings and unanticipated capital expenditures.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company currently
pays a preferential regular distribution on the Series F, Series G and Series H
Preferred Stock at annual rates of $2.3125, $2.15625 and $2.075 per share,
respectively.&#160; No distribution may be made
on the Company&#146;s common stock unless all accrued distributions have been made
with respect to each series of the Company&#146;s preferred stock.&#160; No assurance can be given that the Company </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">12</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">will  be able
to maintain its distribution rate on its common stock or make required  distributions
with respect to the Series F, Series G and Series H Preferred  Stock.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Future distributions by
the Company will be at the discretion of the Board of Directors and will depend
on the actual funds available for distribution of the Company, its financial
condition, capital requirements, the annual distribution requirements under the
REIT provisions of the Internal Revenue Code and such other factors as the
Board of Directors deems relevant.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company has
established the Direct Stock Purchase and Distribution Reinvestment Plan (the
&#147;DSPDRP&#148;) under which holders of common stock (and Series F, Series G and
Series H Preferred Stock) can elect automatically to reinvest their
distributions in additional shares of common stock and/or to make optional
purchases of common stock free of brokerage commissions and charges of at least
$250, but not more than $5,000 in any given month.&#160; To fulfill its obligations under the DSPDRP, the Company may
either issue additional shares of common stock or repurchase common stock in
the open market.&#160; The Company may elect
to sell shares under the DSPDRP at up to a 5% discount, but did not sell any
shares at a discount in 2003.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Information related to
securities authorized for issuance under equity compensation plans as required
in paragraph (d)(2) of this Item is incorporated by reference to the Company&#146;s
definitive proxy statement to be filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.</FONT></P>

FINANCIAL DATA</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH FORWARD-LOOKING STATEMENTS</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">This and other sections
of this Annual Report contain certain forward-looking statements within the
meaning of Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and Section
21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, which are intended to
be covered by the safe harbors created thereby. These statements include, but
are not limited to, statements about anticipated growth rate of revenues and
expenses, planned asset dispositions, disposition pricing, and planned
acquisition and developments.&#160; Although
the Company believes that the assumptions underlying the forward-looking
statements are reasonable, any of the assumptions could be inaccurate and,
therefore, there can be no assurance that the forward-looking statements
included in this report on Form 10-K will prove to be accurate. In light of the
significant uncertainties inherent in the forward-looking statements included
herein, the inclusion of such information should not be regarded as a
representation by the Company or any other person that the objectives and plans
of the Company will be achieved. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The following are risks
that the Company believes could cause results to differ from projected or
forecasted results or could have a material adverse effect on the Company&#146;s
business.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>The
Company&#146;s ability to make distributions may be adversely affected by factors
beyond its control</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s ability to
generate sufficient cash flow in order to pay common dividends to its
shareholders depends on its ability to generate funds from operations in excess
of capital expenditure requirements and common dividends, and/or to have access to
the markets for debt and equity financing. Funds from operations and the value
of the Company&#146;s properties may be less because of factors which are beyond the
Company&#146;s control. Such events or conditions could include:</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Currently, the Company
relies on external funding sources to fully fund the payment of distributions
to shareholders at the current rate.&#160;
While the Company has sufficient liquidity to permit distributions at
current rates through additional borrowings, any significant and sustained
deterioration in operations could result in the Company&#146;s financial resources
being insufficient to pay distributions to shareholders at the current rate, in
which event the Company would be required to cut the distribution rate.&#160; Any decline in the Company&#146;s funds from
operations or property values because of these factors which are beyond its
control could adversely affect the Company&#146;s ability to make distributions to
its shareholders and could have a material adverse effect on the Company&#146;s
stock price.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Debt
level and refinancing risk may adversely affect financial condition and
operating results</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">At December 31, 2003, the
Company had total debt outstanding of $951.9 million. Payments of principal and
interest on borrowings may leave the Company with insufficient cash resources
to operate the Communities or pay distributions required to be paid in order
for the Company to maintain its qualification as a REIT. The Company currently
intends to limit its total debt to around 60% of the undepreciated book value
of its assets, although the Company&#146;s charter and bylaws do not limit its debt
levels. Circumstances may cause the Company to exceed that target from time to
time. As of December 31, 2003, the Company&#146;s ratio of debt to undepreciated
book value was approximately 54%. The Company&#146;s Board of Directors can modify
this policy at any time which could allow the Company to become more highly
leveraged and decrease its ability to make distributions to its
shareholders.&#160; In addition, the Company
must repay its debt upon maturity, and the inability to access debt or equity
capital at attractive rates could adversely affect the Company&#146;s financial condition
and/or its funds from operations.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Variable
interest rates may adversely affect our funds from operations</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">At December 31, 2003,
effectively $216.6 million of the Company&#146;s debt bore interest at a variable
rate and was unhedged and uncapped. In addition, the Company may incur
additional debt in the future that also bears interest at variable rates.
Variable-rate debt creates higher debt service requirements if market interest
rates increase, which would adversely affect the Company&#146;s funds from
operations and the amounts available to pay distributions to shareholders.&#160; The Company&#146;s $611 million secured credit
facility with Prudential Mortgage Capital, credit enhanced by Fannie Mae, is
predominately a floating rate facility, the interest rates on which have been
hedged by means of a number of interest rate swaps and caps.&#160; Upon the termination of these swaps and
caps, the Company will be exposed to the risks of varying interest rates.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Increasing insurance costs may negatively impact financial
condition</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Because the Company has
substantial real estate holdings, the cost of insuring its communities is a
significant component of expense.&#160;
Premiums for property and casualty insurance have risen significantly in
recent years.&#160; If the cost of property
and casualty insurance continues to rise, its cost of doing business </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">16</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">would  likely
rise, which may in turn negatively impact the Company&#146;s financial  condition and
its ability to pay its dividend.</FONT></FONT> </P>


<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>CRITICAL
ACCOUNTING POLICIES AND ESTIMATES</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The following discussion
and analysis of financial condition and results of operations are based upon
the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements, and the notes thereto, which
have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted
in the United States of America.&#160; The
preparation of these consolidated financial statements requires the Company to
make a number of estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts and
disclosures in the consolidated financial statements.&#160; On an ongoing basis, the Company evaluates its estimates and
assumptions based upon historical experience and various other factors and
circumstances.&#160; The Company believes
that its estimates and assumptions are reasonable in the circumstances;
however, actual results may differ from these estimates and assumptions under
different future conditions.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company believes that
the estimates and assumptions that are most important to the portrayal of its
financial condition and results of operations, in that they require the most
subjective judgments, form the basis of accounting policies deemed to be most
critical.&#160; These critical accounting
policies include capitalization of expenditures and depreciation of assets,
impairment of long-lived assets, including goodwill, and fair value of
derivative financial instruments.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Capitalization
of expenditures and depreciation of assets</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company carries its
real estate assets at their depreciated cost.&#160;
Depreciation is computed on a straight-line basis over the estimated
useful lives of the related assets, which range from 8 to 40 years for land
improvements and buildings, to 5 years for furniture, fixtures, and equipment,
and 3 years for computers, all of which are judgmental determinations.&#160; Repairs and maintenance costs are expensed
as incurred while significant improvements, renovations, and replacements are
capitalized.&#160; The cost to complete any
deferred repairs and maintenance at properties acquired by the Company in order
to elevate the condition of the property to the Company&#146;s standards are
capitalized as incurred.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Impairment
of long-lived assets, including goodwill</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company accounts for
long-lived assets in accordance with the provisions of Statement No. 144,
Accounting for the Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets (Statement 144)
and evaluates its goodwill for impairment under Statement No. 142, Goodwill and
Other Intangible Assets (Statement 142). The Company evaluates its goodwill for
impairment on an annual basis in the
Company&#146;s fiscal fourth quarter, or sooner if a goodwill impairment indicator
is identified. The Company periodically evaluates its long-lived assets,
including its investments in real estate and goodwill, for indicators that
would suggest that the carrying amount of the assets may not be recoverable.
The judgments regarding the existence of such indicators are based on factors
such as operating performance, market conditions, and legal factors.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">To evaluate goodwill and
long-lived assets for impairment, the Company estimates future operating
cash flows and uses these cash flow estimates to determine the asset&#146;s fair
value. In the apartment industry, the primary method used for determining fair
values is to divide annual operating cash flows by an appropriate
capitalization rate. The Company determines the appropriate capitalization rate
by reviewing the prevailing rates in the Community&#146;s market or submarket.</FONT></P>


<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">17</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2"><I>Fair  value
of derivative financial instruments</I></FONT></FONT> </P>


<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company utilizes
certain derivative financial instruments, primarily interest rate swaps, during
the normal course of business to manage, or hedge, the interest rate risk
associated with the Company&#146;s variable rate debt or as hedges in anticipation
of future debt transactions to manage well-defined interest rate risk
associated with the transaction.&#160; The
valuation of the derivative financial instruments under SFAS No. 133 requires
the Company to make estimates and judgments that affect the fair value of the
instruments.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In order for a derivative
contract to be designated as a hedging instrument, the relationship between the
hedging instrument and the hedged item must be highly effective. The Company
performs effectiveness tests using the change in the variable cash flows method
at the inception of the hedge and for each reporting period thereafter, through
the term of the hedging instruments. Any amounts determined to be ineffective
are recorded in earnings.&#160; The fair
value of the hedges are recorded to accumulated other comprehensive income.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">While the Company&#146;s
calculation of hedge effectiveness contains some subjective determinations, the
historical correlation of the cash flows of the hedging instruments and the
underlying hedged item are measured by the Company before entering into the
hedging relationship and have been highly related.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>OVERVIEW OF THE YEAR ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2003</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
Company&#146;s operating results for 2003 were impacted by continued economic
weakness. The Company believes that the primary factor impacting demand for its
apartments is job formation, which was slightly negative or static in most of the
Company&#146;s markets during 2003. This reduced the occupancy of its apartments,
affected its ability to grow rents, and increased the amount of concessions
that it had to offer to attract residents. Advertising and marketing
expenditures also had to be increased to attract new residents. The Company
regards single family housing as the primary competition for its existing
residents, and low interest rates that existed throughout the year allowed
its residents to purchase homes and impacted the Company&#146;s occupancy rates. The
Company began to see some improvement in the fourth quarter and expects
operations to improve as the economy improves. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Offsetting
the impact to operations, the Company was able to continue its debt refinancing strategy and take advantage of the low
interest rate environment by reducing the interest rates on its variable rate
debt. As a result, the Company was able to lower its average interest rate
and experienced interest expense savings. The Company was also able
to lower the dividend payments on its preferred stock by redeeming the
Preferred Series A, B &amp; C and issuing a new series of preferred stock,
Series H at a lower yield.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
Company achieved external growth during 2003 by following its acquisition
strategy to invest in large and mid-sized growing markets in the southeastern
United States and in Texas. The Company made acquisitions both directly and
through a joint venture partnership with Crow Holdings. The Company also purchased
the 2/3 share of its joint venture owned by Blackstone Real Estate Advisors
that was formed in 1999. The Company funded part of these purchases through
some selective direct sales of shares of common stock. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
financings and acquisitions made during 2003 helped the Company continue its
strategy of improving the flexibility of its balance sheet and enhancing its
ability to strengthen its dividend coverage.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">18</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
following is a discussion of the consolidated financial condition and results of
operations of the Company for the years ended December 31, 2003, 2002, and
2001.&#160; This discussion should be read in
conjunction with all of the consolidated financial statements included in this
Annual Report on Form 10-K.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">As of December 31, 2003,
the total number of apartment units the Company owned or had an ownership
interest in, including the properties owned by the Company&#146;s joint ventures was
35,734 in 127 Communities, compared to the 33,923 apartment units in 123
Communities owned at December 31, 2002, and the 33,411 apartment units in 122
Communities owned at December 31, 2001.&#160;
For properties owned 100% by the Company, the average monthly rental per
apartment unit, excluding units in lease-up, increased to $667 at December 31,
2003 from $661 at December 31, 2002 and $660 at December 31, 2001.&#160; For these same units, overall occupancy at
December 31, 2003, 2002 and 2001 was 92.7%, 91.9%, and 92.7%,
respectively.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>RESULTS OF OPERATIONS</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>COMPARISON OF THE YEAR ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2003 TO THE YEAR
ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2002</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Comparisons of income
from property operations for the years ended December 31, 2003 and 2002 were
impacted by four main factors. First, as a result of the buyout of the
partnership interest in Bre/Maac Associates, LLC, (the &#147;BRE/MAAC Buyout&#148;), the
Company&#146;s joint venture with Blackstone Real Estate Advisors (&#147;Blackstone&#148;),
the Company&#146;s consolidated financials for 2003 include the impact of
approximately four months of operations of the 10 properties which were
previously owned by the joint venture and accounted for using the equity
method. Second, the Company acquired four properties in 2003 (one of which was
subsequently transferred to Mid-America CH/Realty, LP, the Company&#146;s joint
venture with Crow Holdings). Third, during the years 2003 and 2002, the Company
still had three development communities which were in various stages of
lease-up. Finally, the Company&#146;s performance during 2003 and 2002 was impacted
by changes in performance of the communities that were held throughout both periods.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Property revenues for
2003 increased by approximately $7,713,000 due primarily to increases of (i)
$6,156,000 from the BRE/MAAC Buyout, (ii) $3,841,000 from the acquisitions of
Green Oaks, Los Rios Park, Legacy Pines and Lighthouse Court apartments in 2003
(the &#147;2003 Acquisitions&#148;), and (iii) $1,431,000 from the development
communities.&#160; These increases were partially offset by a decrease in property revenues of $3,715,000 from the
communities owned throughout both periods.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Property operating expenses
include costs for property personnel, building repairs and maintenance, real
estate taxes and insurance, utilities, landscaping and other property related
costs.&#160; As a percentage of total
property revenues, property operating expenses increased to 42.0% in 2003
compared to 40% in 2002.&#160; Property
operating expenses for 2003 increased by approximately $7,996,000 due primarily
to increases of (i) $2,999,000 due to the BRE/MAAC Buyout, (ii) $2,796,000 from
the communities held throughout both periods, (iii) $1,908,000 due to the 2003
Acquisitions, and (iv) $293,000 due to the development communities.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Included in the above is
real estate taxes and insurance which increased approximately $2,994,000 from
2002 to 2003 due to increases of (i) $1,220,000 due to increased insurance
costs associated with the renewal of the Company&#146;s property and casualty
insurance and (ii) $1,774,000 due to increases in real estate taxes, $1,393,000
of which was related to the BRE/MAAC Buyout and 2003 Acquisitions.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">19</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Depreciation and
amortization expense increased by approximately $3,908,000 from the prior year
primarily due to increases of (i) $2,304,000 due to the BRE/MAAC Buyout, (ii)
$1,460,000 due to the 2003 Acquisitions, (iii) $120,000 due to the communities
owned throughout both periods and (iv) $24,000 from the development
communities.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">General and
administrative expense increased 8.6% or $570,000 as compared to the prior
year. This increase was mainly related to increased compensation incentives and
salaries, partially related to the addition of new personnel hired to address
recent regulatory requirements.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Property management
expenses decreased 2.3% or $198,000 as compared to the prior year.&#160; The decrease was mainly due to reductions in
bonuses.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Interest expense decreased
approximately $3,416,000 from 2002 due primarily to the Company&#146;s ability to
take advantage of the decline in interest rates in 2002 and 2003.&#160; The Company&#146;s average borrowing cost at
December 31, 2003 was 5.4% as compared to 5.8% on December 31, 2002. &#160;</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">For the years ended
December 31, 2003, and 2002, the Company recorded net gains on disposition of
assets and insurance settlement proceeds totaling $2,942,000, mainly related to insurance settlements from the fire
 at the Company headquarters in March 2002, and $397,000,
primarily related to insurance settlements, respectively.&#160;</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In 2003 and 2002, the
Company refinanced several of its communities primarily to take advantage of
the lower interest rate environment.&#160;
This resulted in a gain of $111,000 related to the early extinguishment
of debt in 2003 and a loss of approximately $1,444,000 in 2002.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In 2003, the Company
recorded a gain on discontinued operations of $1,919,000 related to the sale of
the Crossings apartments in 2003.&#160; No
properties were sold in 2002.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">As a result of the
foregoing, net income increased by $4,065,000 in 2003 over 2002.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>COMPARISON OF THE YEAR ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2002 TO THE YEAR
ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2001</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Property revenues for
2002 increased by approximately $955,000 due primarily to increases of (i)
$2,707,000 from the development communities and (ii) $1,424,000 from the acquisition
of the Preston Hills apartments in 2002 (&#147;2002 Acquisitions&#148;).&#160; These increases were partially offset by
decreases of (i) $2,104,000 due to the sales of the Advantages and Canyon Creek
apartments in 2001 (&#147;2001 Dispositions&#148;), and (ii) $1,072,000 from the
communities owned throughout both periods.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Property operating
expenses include costs for property personnel, building repairs and
maintenance, real estate taxes and insurance, utilities, landscaping and other
property related costs.&#160; As a percentage
of total property revenues, property operating expenses increased to 40.0% in
2002 compared to 38.7% in 2001.&#160;
Property operating expenses for 2002 increased by approximately
$3,306,000 due primarily to increases of (i) $589,000 due to the development
communities, (ii) $571,000 due to the 2002 Acquisitions, and (iii) $3,021,000
due to the communities owned throughout both periods.&#160; These increases were partially offset by a decrease of $875,000
from the 2001 Dispositions.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Included in the above is
real estate taxes and insurance which increased approximately $2,354,000 from
2001 to 2002 due to increases of (i) $1,598,000 due to increased insurance
costs associated with the </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">20</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">renewal  of the
Company&#146;s property and casualty insurance and (ii) $756,000 due to  increases in
real estate taxes.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Depreciation and
amortization expense increased by approximately $3,185,000 from the prior year
primarily due to increases of (i) $874,000 due to the development communities,
(ii) $374,000 due to the 2002 Acquisitions and (iii) $2,279,000 due to the
communities owned throughout both periods.&#160;
These increases were partially offset by a decrease of $342,000 from the
2001 Dispositions.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">General and
administrative expense increased 2.2% or $143,000 as compared to the prior
year.&#160; Increases in D&amp;O insurance
premiums, bank service charges due to the reduction of cash balances held by
the Company throughout the year, increased compensation incentives, increased
software maintenance expense, and increased legal and director fees due to new
regulatory and compliance requirements were partially offset by a decrease in
airplane repairs from the prior year and the absence of an airplane lease in
2002 following the purchase of a plane to reduce expenses.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Property management expenses
decreased 9.7% or $928,000 as compared to the prior year.&#160; The decrease was mainly due to reductions in
bonuses and salaries, reduced health insurance costs and reduced franchise and
excise taxes from 2001 which year included a one-time franchise and excise tax
settlement.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Interest expense
decreased approximately $3,150,000 from 2001 due primarily to the Company&#146;s
ability to take advantage of the decline in interest rates in the second half
of 2001 and throughout 2002.&#160; The
Company&#146;s average borrowing cost at December 31, 2002 was 5.8% as compared to
6.3% on December 31, 2001.&#160; The average
maturity on the Company&#146;s debt was 10.9 years at December 31, 2002.&#160; Amortization of deferred financing costs was
$2,712,000 and $2,352,000 for 2002 and 2001, respectively.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">For the year ended
December 31, 2002, the Company recorded a net gain on disposition of assets and
insurance settlement proceeds totaling $397,000 primarily related to insurance
settlements.&#160; For the year ended December
31, 2001, the Company recorded a net gain on disposition of assets and
insurance settlement proceeds totaling $11,933,000 primarily related to the
disposition of two properties during the year.&#160;
</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In 2002 and 2001, the
Company refinanced several of its communities primarily to take advantage of
the lower interest rate environment.&#160;
This resulted in a loss of approximately $1,444,000 due to the early
extinguishment of debt in 2002 and approximately $1,189,000 in 2001.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">As a result of the
foregoing, net income decreased by $12,557,000 in 2002 over 2001.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>FUNDS FROM OPERATIONS</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Funds from operations
(&#147;FFO&#148;) represents net income (computed in accordance with accounting
principles generally accepted in the United States of America, or &#147;GAAP&#148;)
excluding extraordinary items, minority interest in Operating Partnership
income, gain or loss on sale of discontinued operations and insurance
settlement proceeds, plus depreciation and amortization of real estate, and
adjustments for joint ventures to reflect FFO on the same basis.&#160; This definition of FFO is in accordance with
the National Association of Real Estate Investment Trust&#146;s (&#147;NAREIT&#148;)
recommended definition.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s policy is
to expense the cost of interior painting, vinyl flooring, and blinds as
incurred for stabilized properties.&#160; During
the stabilization period for acquisition properties, these items are</FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">21</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">capitalized  as
part of the total repositioning program of newly acquired properties, and,  thus are not
deducted in calculating FFO.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">FFO should not be
considered as an alternative to net income or any other GAAP measurement of
performance, as an indicator of operating performance or as an alternative to
cash flow from operating, investing, and financing activities as a measure of
liquidity.&#160; The Company believes that
FFO is helpful in understanding the Company&#146;s operating performance in that
such calculation excludes depreciation expense on real estate assets.&#160; The Company believes that GAAP historical
cost depreciation of real estate assets is generally not correlated with
changes in the value of those assets, whose value does not diminish predictably
over time, as historical cost depreciation implies.&#160; The Company&#146;s calculation of FFO may differ from the methodology
for calculating FFO utilized by other REITs and, accordingly, may not be
comparable to such other REITs.&#160; </FONT></P>

reconciliation of FFO to net income for the three years ended December 31,
2003, 2002 and 2001 (dollars and shares in thousands):</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Net income increased
during 2003 by approximately $4,065,000 to $20,206,000 versus $16,141,000 in
2002, principally because of reduced interest expenses, a $1,919,000 gain on
the sale of the Crossings apartments which is classified as a discontinued
operation and $2,942,000 net gain on insurance settlement proceeds which were
only partially offset by the increase in depreciation and amortization from
acquisitions. Net income for 2001 was $28,698,000 which included a gain of
$11,933,000 from dispositions of assets and insurance settlement proceeds.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">22</FONT></P>


<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">FFO  increased
during 2003 by approximately $2,014,000 to $55,367,000 versus  $53,353,000 in 2002
principally because of reduced interest expense.&#160; FFO for 2001 was $56,023,000. FFO
for 2003  and 2002 included charges of $5,987,000 and $2,041,000, respectively, for
premiums and original issuance costs associated with the redemption of  preferred stock.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>TRENDS </I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Property performance over
the past two years has been pressured by an imbalance between supply and demand
for apartment units in many of the Company&#146;s markets.&#160; The recent economic downturn and the related low interest rate
environment have combined to contribute to a temporary decline in demand for
apartment units, while allowing delivery levels of newly constructed apartment
units to remain consistent with historical averages.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The recent economic
environment has impacted demand in two main ways: 1) producing lower job
growth, which reduced the number of potential renters in most of the Company&#146;s
markets, and 2) producing lower interest rates which has increased the
affordability of single family housing, prompting more renters to purchase
homes.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On the supply side, the
declining interest rates have provided an incentive to developers to construct
new apartment units in many of the Company&#146;s markets, especially in the larger
metropolitan markets.&#160; Delivery of these new
units during this period of weakened apartment demand has increased
competition, adding pressure to apartment occupancy levels and pricing in a
number of the Company&#146;s markets.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">As part of its strategy
to create continued stable and growing performance, the Company maintains a
portfolio of properties diversified across large metropolitan markets,
mid-sized markets, and smaller tier markets, as defined by population
levels.&#160; During the recent economic
downturn, the Company&#146;s smaller tier and mid-sized markets produced more stable
performance, while it&#146;s larger metropolitan markets proved more susceptible to
declining job formation and apartment supply imbalances.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company is beginning
to see indications of stronger job growth in many of its markets, which could
indicate an improvement in the general economic environment. As the economic
environment improves, the Company expects to see more household formations and
increasing interest rates, which should combine to increase the number of
apartment renters.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company expects that
this increase in demand will generate stronger property performance across the
Company&#146;s portfolio. The Company&#146;s large-tier markets, which have been under
the most pressure during the economic downturn, should begin to absorb the
oversupply of new apartment units and return to historical occupancy and
pricing levels, while the Company&#146;s smaller-tier and mid-sized markets would
benefit from improving market fundamentals which support continued stable
growth.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Over the long term,
general demographic trends are expected to favor apartment owners, as
immigration growth, combined with the increasing demand for rental housing from
the &#147;echo boomers&#148; (children of the &#147;baby boomers&#148;) is expected to produce more
apartment renters over the next ten years.&#160;
The Company believes its portfolio location throughout the Southeast and
South central regions of the country position it well to take advantage of
these improving demographic trends. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Net cash flow provided by
operating activities remained relatively stable at $79,241,000 for 2003
compared to $81,076,000 for 2002.</FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">23</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Net cash used in
investing activities grew during 2003 to $139,934,000 from $34,182,000 in
2002.&#160; This increase was primarily due
to (i) the purchase of Legacy Pines for $21,500,000, Green Oaks for $18,966,00,
the partnership interest in our joint venture with Blackstone for $21,853,000,
Los Rios Park for $32,500,000 and Lighthouse Court for $40,092,000 compared to
one acquisition of Preston Hills in 2002 for $33,900,000, and (ii) in 2003
dispositions totaled $24,906,000, including the transfer of a 2/3 interest in
Green Oaks to CH/Realty for $12,644,000, compared to dispositions of
$36,841,000 in 2002.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Capital improvements to
stabilized properties during the 2003 and 2002 totaled $23,211,000 and
$23,083,000, respectively.&#160; Actual
capital expenditures are summarized below (dollars in thousands):</FONT></P>
