<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In 2002,
corporate/commercial capital improvements was mainly related to the fire at the
Company&#146;s corporate headquarters in March of 2002, for which the Company was
reimbursed with insurance proceeds of $5,235,000 in 2003.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Net cash provided by
financing activities was approximately $60,251,000 for 2003 compared to net
cash used in financing activities of $48,492,000 in 2002.&#160; During 2003 the Company increased its
borrowings under its credit lines by $218,399,000 as compared to an increase of
$60,623,000 in 2002 to accommodate refinancing activities and property
acquisitions.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In 2003, the Company
negotiated an increase from $550 million to $611 million in the borrowing
capacity of its existing secured credit facility with Prudential Mortgage
Capital, credit enhanced by Fannie Mae (the &#147;FNMA Facility&#148;).&#160; The expanded capacity may be utilized only
as additional collateral is pledged to secure the facility.&#160; At December 31, 2003 the FNMA Facility had
an outstanding balance of $555.7 million with an available borrowing base
capacity of $596.1 million.&#160; $303
million of the FNMA Facility expires in 2004, renewable for two successive
5-year terms, $249 million expires in 2007, and the remaining amount expires in
2008, both renewable for a 5-year term.&#160;
The Company plans to utilize the additional facility capacity to
refinance debt maturities over the next 18 months.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The FNMA Facility
provides for both fixed and variable rate borrowings.&#160; The interest rate on the variable portion renews every 90 days
and is based on the FNMA Discount Mortgage Backed Security (&#147;DMBS&#148;) rate on the
date of renewal, which has typically approximated three-month LIBOR less an
average spread of 0.07%, plus a credit enhancement fee of 0.60% to 0.72% based
on the outstanding borrowings.&#160; The variable
interest rate at December 31, 2003 was 1.8% on variable rate borrowings of
$445.7 million.&#160; Fixed rate borrowings
under the FNMA Facility totaled $110 million at December 31, 2003, at interest
rates (inclusive of credit-enhancement fees) from 5.77% to 7.71%, and
maturities from 2006 to 2009. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Compass Bank provides an
unsecured credit facility to the Company.&#160;
Outstanding borrowings under this facility at December 31, 2003 were $20
million at a rate of 1.66%.</FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">24</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">The  Company
currently maintains a $40 million secured credit facility with two  banks led by AmSouth
Bank.&#160; There was no  outstanding balance under this facility at December 31, 2003.&#160; Available
borrowing base capacity under this  facility was $19.0 million at December 31, 2003.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Each of the Company&#146;s
credit facilities is subject to various covenants and conditions on usage
including the maintenance of certain financial ratios The total amount of
credit which is made available is governed by lender formulas defining asset
valuation. If the Company were to fail to satisfy a condition to borrowing, the
available credit under one or more of the facilities could not be drawn, which
could adversely affect the Company&#146;s liquidity.&#160; Moreover, if the Company were to fail to make a payment or violate
a covenant under a credit facility, after applicable cure periods one or more
of its lenders could declare a default, accelerate the due date for repayment
of all amounts outstanding and/or foreclose on properties securing such
facilities which may cause the Company to be declared in default by its other
lenders.&#160; Any such event could have a
material adverse effect on the Company.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">At December 31, 2003, the
Company had a promissory note with Union Planters National Bank (&#147;Union
Planters&#148;) for $40 million at a variable rate of 2.2%.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company uses interest
rate swaps to manage its current and future interest rate risk.&#160;&#160; The Company has nine interest rate swaps
with a total notional balance of $275 million which have variable legs based on
one or three-month LIBOR, and fixed legs with an average rate of 6.2%.&#160; The swaps have expirations between 2005 and
2010, and have to date proven to be highly effective hedges of the Company&#146;s
designated variable rate borrowings of its FNMA Facility.&#160; The Company has designed these interest rate
swaps as cash flow hedges on its FNMA Facility.&#160; Through the use of these swaps the Company believes it has
effectively fixed the borrowing rate during these periods of $275 million of
variable rate borrowings issued through the FNMA Facility, leaving only $170.7
million of the FNMA Facility of which the interest rate has not been fixed or
hedged. The Company also has a $55.6 million Tax-Free Bond Facility with
FNMA.&#160; The Company has five interest
rate swaps with a total notional amount of $42.7 million which have variable
legs based on the BMA Municipal Swap Index and fixed legs with an average rate
of 4.3%.&#160; These swaps expire in 2007 and
2008, and have to date proven to be highly effective hedges of the designated
borrowings of the Tax-Free Bond Facility. The Company also entered into a cap agreement on a notional amount of
$6.8 million within the Tax-Free Bond Facility.&#160; The 5-year cap agreement has a strike rate of 6% as indexed on
the BMA Municipal Swap Index. Additionally, the Company has one interest rate
swap with a notional amount of $25 million which has a variable leg
based on three-month LIBOR, and a fixed leg with an average rate of 4.6% which
expires in 2009 and has to date proven to be a highly effective hedge of the
designated borrowings of Union Planters. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company has also
executed one forward interest rate swap with a notional balance of $40 million
which goes into effect in 2004.&#160; The
variable leg of the forward interest rate swap is based on three-month LIBOR and
the fixed leg has an average rate of 4.9%.&#160;
The swap expires in 2010 and is designated as a cash flow hedge on
future planned refinancings.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In March 2003, the
Company had approximating $151 million of debt maturing including the $142
million of bond indebtedness of Mid-America Capital Partners, L.P., which it
funded by debt issued under the FNMA Facility. The rate on the maturing debt
was 6.5% and the rate on the replacement debt which was partially pre-set
through interest rate swaps was 5.6%.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The weighted average
interest rate and the weighted average maturity at December 31, 2003, for the
$951.9 million of debt outstanding were 5.4% and 10.6 years compared to 5.8%
and 10.9 years on $803.7 million of debt outstanding at December 31, 2002.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">25</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">On  July 10,
2003, in an underwritten public offering, the Company sold 5,600,000  shares of its 8.30%
Series H Cumulative Redeemable Preferred Stock (&#147;Series H&#148;)  at $25 per share
less an underwriting discount of $0.7875 per share.&#160; The net proceeds of the sale
were applied to  the redemption of all the issued and outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s
9.5%  Series A Cumulative Preferred Stock and 9 3/8% Series C Cumulative Redeemable
Preferred Stock as well as 1,600,000 shares of the 1,938,830 issued and  outstanding
shares of the Company&#146;s 8 7/8% Series B Cumulative Preferred Stock  (&#147;Series B&#148;)
on August 12, 2003.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On July 16, 2003, the underwriters of the Company&#146;s
Series H offering exercised an option to purchase an additional 525,000 shares
of the Series H preferred stock for $25 per share less the underwriting
discount, and on August 4, 2003, the underwriters exercised an option to
purchase the remaining additional 75,000 shares of the Series H preferred stock
for $25 per share less the underwriting discount.&#160; The net proceeds were used to redeem the remaining issued and
outstanding shares of the Series B preferred stock on August 18, 2003.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On August 22, 2003, the Company sold 700,000 shares
of its common stock to certain advisory clients of Cohen &amp; Steers Capital
Management, Inc. The stock was sold at a price of $28.40 per share. The
$19,870,000 in net proceeds from the sale were used to partially fund the
purchase of the BreMaac limited partnership interest held by Blackstone.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On September 19, 2003, the Company sold 665,000
shares of its common stock to certain advisory clients of Cohen &amp; Steers
Capital Management, Inc. and to Scudder RREEF Real Estate Fund II, Inc. The
stock was sold at a price of $29.36 per share. The $19,500,000 in net proceeds
from the sale were used to partially fund the purchase of the Los Rios
Park apartments.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On December 2, 2003, the Company sold 400,000
shares of its common stock to RREEF America, L.L.C. on behalf of itself and
Scudder RREEF Real Estate Fund II, Inc. The stock was sold at a price of $30.00
per share. The $11,996,000 in net proceeds from the sale were used to partially
fund the acquisition of the Lighthouse Court apartments.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On October 16, 2002, the
Company closed the sale of 470,000 shares of a new 9&#188;% Series F Cumulative
Redeemable Preferred Stock (&#147;Series F Preferred Stock&#148;).&#160; An additional 4,500 shares were sold as part
of the underwriters option on November 8, 2002.&#160; All of the shares were sold at $25 per share for an aggregate
principal amount of $11.86 million.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">On October 28, 2002, the
Company privately placed 400,000 shares of a new 8 5/8% Series G Cumulative
Redeemable Preferred Stock (&#147;Series G Preferred Stock&#148;) at $25 per share for an
aggregate principal amount of $10 million. On or after October 10, 2004, the
Company or the investor may give the required one year&#146;s notice to redeem or
put, respectively, all or part of the Series G Preferred Stock beginning on or
after October 10, 2005 in increments of $1 million. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The net proceeds from the
issuances of the Series F Preferred Stock and Series G Preferred Stock along
with $5 million of debt were used to repurchase and retire all of the 1,000,000
shares of the Company&#146;s Series E Cumulative Redeemable Preferred Stock at a 7%
premium (totaling $2.0 million including the write-off of previous issuance costs)
for an aggregate purchase price of $26.75 million.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company believes that
it has adequate resources to fund both its current operations, annual
refurbishment of its properties, and incremental investment in new apartment
properties.&#160; The Company is relying on
the efficient operation of the financial markets to finance debt maturities,
and also is heavily reliant on the creditworthiness of FNMA, which provides
credit enhancement for nearly $611 million of</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">26</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">the  Company&#146;s
outstanding debt. &#160;The market  for FNMA DMBS, which in the Company&#146;s experience
is highly effective with  three-month LIBOR interest rates, is also an important
component of the  Company&#146;s liquidity and swap effectiveness.&#160; In the event
that the FNMA DMBS market becomes less efficient, or the  credit of FNMA becomes
impaired, the Company would seek alternative sources of  debt financing.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company believes that
cash provided by operations is adequate and anticipates that it will continue
to be adequate in both the short and long-term to meet operating requirements
(including recurring capital expenditures at the communities) and payment of
distributions by the Company in accordance with REIT requirements under the
Internal Revenue Code.&#160; The Company has
loan covenants that limit the total amount of distributions, but believes that
it is unlikely that these will be a limiting factor on the Company&#146;s future
levels of distributions based on the Company&#146;s current range of forecast of
operating performance.&#160; The Company
expects to meet its liquidity requirements, such as scheduled mortgage debt
maturities, property acquisitions, expansions, and non-recurring capital
expenditures, through collateralized borrowings, potential joint venture
transactions and the Company&#146;s credit facilities.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Currently, the Company&#146;s
operating cash flow is insufficient to fully fund the payment of distributions
to shareholders at the current rate.&#160;
While the Company has sufficient liquidity to permit distributions at
current rates through additional borrowings, any significant deterioration in
operations could result in the Company&#146;s financial resources to be insufficient
to pay distributions to shareholders at the current rate, in which event the
Company would be required to cut the distribution rate.&#160; </FONT></P>

reflects the Company&#146;s total contractual cash obligations which consists of its
long-term debt as of December 31, 2003 (dollars in 000&#146;s):</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>OFF-BALANCE SHEET ARRANGEMENTS</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">At December 31, 2003 and
2002, the Company did not have any relationships with unconsolidated entities
or financial partnerships, such as entities often referred to as &#147;structured
finance&#148; or &#147;special purpose entities&#148;, established for the purpose of
facilitating off-balance sheet arrangements or other contractually narrow or
limited purposes.&#160; The Company&#146;s joint
venture with Blackstone (terminated in 2003) was established in order to raise
capital through asset sales to fund development while acquiring management fees
to help offset the reduction in FFO from the sale.&#160; The Company&#146;s joint venture with Crow Holdings was established to
acquire approximately $150 million of multifamily properties.&#160; In addition, the Company does not engage in
trading activities involving non-exchange traded contracts.&#160; As such, the Company is not materially exposed
to any financing, liquidity, market, or credit risk that could arise if it had
engaged in such relationships.&#160; The
Company does not have any relationships or transactions with persons or
entities that derive benefits from their non-independent relationships with </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">27</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">the  Company or
its related parties other than what is disclosed in Item 8.,  Financial Statements and
Supplementary Data - Notes to Consolidated Financial  Statements, Note 11.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s investments
in its real estate joint venture is unconsolidated and is recorded on the
equity method as the Company does not have a controlling interest.&#160; The Company has a mezzanine loan in the
amount of $4.7 million at an average rate of 9% receivable from its joint
venture, CH/Realty.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>INSURANCE</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
Company put in place a new property and casualty insurance program effective
July 1, 2003.&#160; The program is
substantially the same as last year.&#160; In
the opinion of management, property and casualty insurance is in place that
provides adequate coverage to provide financial protection against normal
insurable risks such that it believes that any loss experienced would not have
a significant impact on the Company&#146;s liquidity, financial position, or results
of operations.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>INFLATION</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Substantially all of the
resident leases at the Communities allow, at the time of renewal, for adjustments
in the rent payable there under, and thus may enable the Company to seek rent
increases.&#160; Almost all leases are for
one year or less.&#160; The short-term nature
of these leases generally serves to reduce the risk to the Company of the
adverse effects of inflation. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>IMPACT OF RECENTLY ISSUED ACCOUNTING STANDARDS</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In April 2002, the FASB
issued Statement No. 145, Rescission of FASB Statements No. 4, 44, and 64,
Amendment of FASB Statement No. 13, and Technical Corrections (Statement
145).&#160; The rescission of Statement No.
4, Reporting Gains and Losses from Extinguishment of Debt and Statement No. 64,
Extinguishments of Debt made to Satisfy Sinking-Fund Requirements eliminates an
exception to general practice relating to the determination of whether certain items
should be classified as extraordinary and is effective in fiscal years
beginning after May 15, 2002, with earlier implementation encouraged.&#160; The rescission of Statement No. 44 and all
other provisions of Statement 145 are effective for fiscal years beginning
after May 15, 2002.&#160; As a result of the
adoption of Statement 145, the Company reclassified $1,444,000, representing
extraordinary gain (before minority interest adjustment) on early
extinguishment of debt for the twelve months ended December 31, 2002, to a
component of operating income.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In December 2003, The
FASB issued FASB Interpretation No. 46 (revised December 2003), Consolidation
of Variable Interest Entities (&#147;FIN46R&#148;).&#160;
FIN46R replaces FASB Interpretation No. 46, Consolidation of Variable Interest
Entities, which was issued in January 2003, and addresses how a business
enterprise should evaluate whether it has a controlling financial interest in
an entity through means other than voting rights and how, accordingly, it
should consolidate the entity.&#160; The
Company will be required to apply FIN46R to variable interests in variable
interest entities (&#147;VIEs&#148;) created after December 31, 2003.&#160; For variable interests in VIEs created
before January 1, 2004, FIN46R will be applied beginning on January 10,
2005.&#160; For any VIEs that were created
before January 1, 2004 which must be consolidated under FIN46R, the assets,
liabilities and noncontrolling interest of the VIE would initially be measured
at their carrying values with any difference between the net amount added to
the balance sheet and any previously recognized interest being recognized as
the cumulative effect of an accounting change.&#160;
If determining the carrying amounts is not practicable, fair value at
the date FIN46R first applies may be used to measure the assets, liabilities
and noncontrolling interest of the VIE.&#160;
The </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">28</FONT></P>


<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">adoption  of
FIN46R is not expected to have a material impact on the Company&#146;s  consolidated
financial condition or results of operations taken as a whole.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In April 2003, the FASB
issued Statement No. 149, Amendment of Statement No. 133, Accounting for
Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities.&#160;
Statement 149 amends and clarifies financial accounting and reporting
for derivative instruments, including certain derivative instruments embedded
in other contracts (collectively referred to as derivatives) and for hedging
activities under FASB Statement No. 133, Accounting for Derivative Instruments
and Hedging Activities.&#160; Statement 149
is effective for contracts entered into or modified after June 30, 2003.&#160; The adoption of Statement 149 did not have a
material effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial condition or results of
operations taken as a whole.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In May 2003, the FASB
issued Statement No. 150, Accounting for Certain Financial Instruments with
Characteristics of both Liabilities and Equity.&#160; Statement 150 requires issuers to classify as liabilities (or
assets in some circumstances) financial instruments within the scope of the
statement that embody unconditional obligations for the issuer.&#160; Statement 150 was effective for financial
instruments entered into or modified after May 31, 2003, and otherwise was
effective at the beginning of the first interim period beginning after June 15,
2003.&#160; The adoption of Statement 150 had
no effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial condition or results of
operations taken as a whole.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A010"></A>ITEM 7A.&#160; QUANTITATIVE
AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s primary market risk exposure is to changes in interest
rates obtainable on its secured and unsecured borrowings.&#160; At December 31, 2003, 50% of the Company&#146;s
total capitalization consisted of borrowings.&#160;
The Company&#146;s interest rate risk objective is to limit the impact of
interest rate fluctuations on earnings and cash flows and to lower its overall
borrowing costs.&#160; To achieve this
objective, the Company manages its exposure to fluctuations in market interest
rates for its borrowings through the use of fixed rate debt instruments to the
extent that reasonably favorable rates are obtainable with such arrangements
and may enter into derivative financial instruments such as interest rate
swaps, caps and treasury locks to mitigate its interest rate risk on a related
financial instrument or to effectively fix the interest rate on a portion of
its variable debt or on future refinancings.&#160;
The Company does not enter into derivative or interest rate transactions
for trading purposes.&#160; Approximately 77%
of the Company&#146;s outstanding debt was subject to fixed rates with a weighted
average of 6.5% at December 31, 2003.&#160;
The Company regularly reviews interest rate exposure on its outstanding
borrowings in an effort to minimize the risk of interest rate fluctuations.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">29</FONT></P>


<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>

table below provides information about the Company&#146;s financial instruments that
are sensitive to changes in interest rates.&#160;
For debt obligations, the table presents principal cash flows and
related weighted average interest rates by expected maturity dates.&#160; For interest rate swaps and the Company&#146;s
interest rate cap, the table presents the notional amount of the swaps and cap
and the years in which they expire.&#160; Weighted
average variable rates are based on rates in effect at the reporting date
(dollars in 000&#146;s).&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A011"></A>ITEM 8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FINANCIAL STATEMENTS AND
SUPPLEMENTARY DATA</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Independent Auditors&#146;
Report, Consolidated Financial Statements and Selected Quarterly Financial
Information are set forth on pages F-1 to F-25 of this Annual Report on Form
10-K.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A012"></A>ITEM 9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CHANGES IN AND DISAGREEMENTS WITH
ACCOUNTANTS ON ACCOUNTING AND FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">There have been no
disagreements with the Company&#146;s independent accountants on any matter of
accounting principles or practices or financial statement disclosure.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A013"></A>ITEM 9A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>EVALUATION OF DISCLOSURE CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company maintains
disclosure controls and procedures that are designed to ensure that information
required to be disclosed in its Exchange Act reports is recorded, processed,
summarized and reported within the time periods specified in the SEC&#146;s rules
and forms, and that such information is accumulated and communicated to the
Company&#146;s management, including its Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial
Officer, as appropriate, to allow timely decisions regarding required
disclosure. Management necessarily applied its judgment in assessing the costs
and benefits of such controls and procedures which, by their nature, can
provide only reasonable assurance regarding management&#146;s control objectives.
The Company also has an investment in an unconsolidated entity which is not
under its control. Consequently, the Company&#146;s disclosure controls and
procedures with respect to this entity are necessarily more limited than those
it maintains with respect to its consolidated subsidiaries.</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">30</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">As  of the end
of the period covered by this report, an evaluation was carried out  under the
supervision and with the participation of the Company&#146;s management,  including the
Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, of the  effectiveness of the design
and operation of the Company&#146;s disclosure controls  and procedures pursuant to Rule
13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e) of the Securities  Exchange Act of 1934 (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;).
Based upon that evaluation, the  Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer
concluded that the  Company&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures are effective in
timely alerting  them to material information relating to the Company (including its
consolidated subsidiaries) that is required to be included in the Company&#146;s
Exchange Act filings. </FONT></FONT> </P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>CHANGES IN INTERNAL CONTROL OVER FINANCIAL REPORTING</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">During
the twelve months ended December 31, 2003, there were no significant changes in
the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting that materially
affected, or that are reasonably likely to affect, the registrant&#146;s internal
control over financial reporting. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><I>Special Note
Regarding Analyst Reports </I></B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Investors
should also be aware that while the Company&#146;s management does, from time to
time, communicate with securities analysts, it is against the Company&#146;s policy
to disclose to them any material non-public information or other confidential
commercial information. Accordingly, shareholders should not assume that the
Company agrees with any statement or report issued by any analyst irrespective
of the content of the statement or report. Furthermore, the Company has a
policy against issuing or confirming financial forecasts or projections issued
by others. Thus, to the extent that reports issued by securities analysts
contain any projections, forecasts or opinions, such reports are not the
responsibility of Mid-America Apartment Communities, Inc.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A014"></A>PART III</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A015"></A>ITEM 10.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;DIRECTORS AND EXECUTIVE OFFICERS OF
THE REGISTRANT</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Incorporated by reference
to the Company&#146;s definitive proxy statement to be filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B><A NAME="A016"></A>ITEM 11.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION</B></FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>INDEPENDENT AUDITORS&#146; REPORT</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Board of Directors
and Shareholders<BR>
Mid-America Apartment Communities, Inc.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of Mid-America
Apartment Communities, Inc. and subsidiaries (the &#147;Company&#148;) as of December 31,
2003 and 2002 and the related consolidated statements of operations,
shareholders&#146; equity and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year
period ended December 31, 2003.&#160; In
connection with our audits of the consolidated financial statements, we have
also audited the accompanying financial statement Schedule III:&#160; Real Estate and Accumulated Depreciation.&#160; These financial statements and the financial
statement schedule are the responsibility of the management of the
Company.&#160; Our responsibility is to
express an opinion on these consolidated financial statements and the financial
statement schedule based on our audits.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
conducted our audits in accordance with auditing standards generally accepted
in the United States of America.&#160; Those
standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable
assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material
misstatement.&#160; An audit includes
examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in
the financial statements.&#160; An audit also
includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates
made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement
presentation.&#160; We believe that our
audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</FONT></P>


<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present
fairly, in all material respects the financial position of the Company as of
December 31, 2003 and 2002, and the results of the their operations and their
cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December 31,
2003, in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United
States of America.&#160; Also, in our
opinion, the related financial statement schedule when considered in
relationship to the basic financial statements taken as a whole, presents
fairly, in all material respects, the information set forth therein.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As described in Note 1,
the consolidated financial statements reflect the Company&#146;s adoption of Statement
of Financial Accounting Standards No. 145, Rescission of FASB Statements
No. 4, 44, and 64, Amendment of FASB Statement No. 13, and Technical Corrections.</FONT></P>

<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2"><B>Mid-America
Apartment Communities,  Inc.<BR>Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements<BR>Years ended
December 31, 2003, 2002 and 2001</B></FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>1. Organization and Summary of Significant Accounting
Policies</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Organization and Formation of the
Company</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Mid-America Apartment
Communities, Inc. (&#147;Mid-America&#148;) is a self-administrated and self-managed real
estate investment trust which owns, acquires and operates multifamily apartment
communities mainly in the southeastern United States, and in Texas.&#160; The company owns and operates 124 apartment
communities principally through its majority owned subsidiary, Mid-America
Apartments, L.P. (the &#147;Operating Partnership&#148;). The Company also owns a 33.33%
interest in a real estate joint venture which owns 3 apartment communities, for
which the Company provides management services.&#160;&#160;&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Basis
of Presentation</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The consolidated
financial statements presented herein include the accounts of Mid-America, the
Operating Partnership, and all other subsidiaries (&#147;the Company&#148;).&#160; The Company owns 51% to 100% of all
consolidated subsidiaries.&#160; The Company
uses the equity method of accounting for its investments in 20 to 50
percent-owned entities for which the Company does not have the ability to
exercise control.&#160; All significant
intercompany accounts and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Minority Interest</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Minority interest in the
accompanying consolidated financial statements relates to the ownership
interest in the Operating Partnership by the holders of Class A Common Units of
the Operating Partnership (&#147;Operating Partnership Units&#148;).&#160; Mid-America is the sole general partner of
the Operating Partnership.&#160; Net income
is allocated to the minority interest based on their respective ownership
percentage of the Operating Partnership.&#160;
Issuance of additional common shares or Operating Partnership Units
changes the ownership of both the minority interest and Mid-America.&#160; Such transactions and the proceeds there
from are treated as capital transactions and result in an allocation between
shareholders&#146; equity and minority interest to account for the change in the
respective percentage ownership of the underlying equity of the Operating Partnership.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s Board of
Directors established economic rights in respect to each Operating Partnership
Unit that were equivalent to the economic rights in respect to each share of
common stock.&#160; The holder of each unit
may redeem their units in exchange for one share of common stock or cash, at
the option of the Company.&#160; The
Operating Partnership has followed the policy of paying the same per unit
distribution in respect to the units as the per share distribution in respect
to the common stock. &#160;Operating
Partnership net income for 2003, 2002 and 2001 was allocated approximately
14.6%, 15.7%, and 16.2%, respectively, to holders of Operating Partnership
Units and 85.4%, 84.3%, and 83.8%, respectively, to Mid-America.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Use of Estimates</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Management of the Company
has made a number of estimates and assumptions relating to the reporting of
assets and liabilities, the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities,
and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses to prepare these financial
statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the
United States of America.&#160; Actual
results could differ from those estimates.</FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-6</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Left Head Italic" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2"><I>Revenue
Recognition</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company leases
multifamily residential apartments under operating leases primarily with terms
of one year or less.&#160; Rental and other
revenues are recorded when earned which is not materially different than on a
straight-line basis.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company records all
gains and losses on real estate in accordance with SFAS No. 66.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Rental Costs</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Costs associated with
rental activities are expensed as incurred.&#160;
Certain costs associated with the lease-up of development projects,
including cost of model units, their furnishings, signs, and &#147;grand openings&#148;
are capitalized and amortized over their respective estimated useful
lives.&#160; All other costs relating to
renting development projects are expensed as incurred.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Cash and Cash Equivalents</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company considers
cash, investments in money market accounts and certificates of deposit with
original maturities of three months or less to be cash equivalents.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Restricted Cash</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Restricted cash consists
of escrow deposits held by lenders for property taxes, insurance, debt service
and replacement reserves.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Real Estate Assets and
Depreciation</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Real estate assets are
carried at depreciated cost.&#160; Repairs
and maintenance costs are expensed as incurred while significant improvements,
renovations, and replacements are capitalized.&#160;
The cost of interior painting, vinyl flooring and blinds are expensed as
incurred.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In conjunction with
acquisitions of properties, the Company&#146;s policy is to provide in its
acquisition budgets adequate funds to complete any deferred maintenance items
to bring the properties to the required standard, including the cost of
replacement appliances, carpet, interior painting, vinyl flooring and
blinds.&#160; These costs are capitalized.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Depreciation is computed
on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the related assets
which range from 8 to 40 years for land improvements and buildings and 5 years
for furniture, fixtures and equipment and 3 years for computers. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">For real estate
acquisitions subsequent to June 30, 2001, the effective date of Statement of
Financial Accounting Standards 141, <I>Business
Combinations</I>, the fair value of the real estate acquired is
allocated to the acquired tangible assets, consisting of land, building,
furniture, fixtures and equipment, and identified intangible assets and
liabilities, consisting of above and below market leases, resident relationship
values and the value of in-place leases.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The fair value of the
tangible assets of an acquired property (land, building, furniture, fixtures
and equipment) is determined by valuing the property as if it were vacant.&#160;&#160; The &#147;as-if-vacant&#148; value is then allocated
to land, building, furniture, fixtures and equipment based on management&#146;s
determination of the relative fair values of these assets.&#160; Management determines the as-if-vacant fair
value of a property using methods similar to those used by independent
appraisers.&#160; Factors considered by
management in performing these analyses include an estimate of&#160; carrying costs&#160; during the period of time that would be required in the current
market conditions to lease-up the property.&#160;
Management includes real estate taxes, insurance, operating expenses and
lost rentals as well as the costs required to execute similar leases in the
estimated carrying costs.&#160;&#160;&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In allocating the fair
value of identified intangible assets and liabilities of an acquired property,
the in-place leases are compared to current market conditions.&#160; Based on these evaluations, management
believes that the leases acquired on each of its property acquisitions were at
market rates since the lease terms do not extend beyond one year. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The fair value of the
in-place leases and resident relationships is measured by the excess of the
purchase price over the as-if-vacant value of the property as described
above.&#160;&#160; The fair value of the in-place
leases and resident relationships is then amortized over the remaining term of
the resident leases.&#160; The amount of
these resident lease intangibles included in real estate assets totaled $4.9
million and $0 as of December 31, 2003 and 2002, respectively and the
amortization recorded as a reduction of property income was $1.4 million and $0
for the years ending December 31, 2003 and 2002, respectively.&#160;&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Goodwill
and Intangible Assets </I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company accounts for
long-lived assets in accordance with the provisions of Statement No. 144,
Accounting for the Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets and evaluates
its goodwill for impairment under Statement No. 142, Goodwill and Other
Intangible Assets.&#160; The Company
evaluates its goodwill for impairment on an annual basis during the Company&#146;s fiscal
fourth quarter. The Company periodically evaluates its long-lived assets,
including its investments in real estate and goodwill, for indicators that
would suggest that the carrying amount of the assets may not be
recoverable.&#160; The judgments regarding
the existence of such indicators are based on factors such as operating
performance, market conditions, and legal factors.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">To evaluate goodwill and
long-lived assets for impairment, the Company estimates future operating
cash flows and uses these cash flow estimates to determine the asset&#146;s fair
value.&#160; In the apartment industry, the
primary method used for determining fair value is to divide annual operating
cash flows by </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-7</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">an  appropriate
capitalization rate.&#160; The  Company determines the appropriate capitalization rate by
reviewing the  prevailing rates in a property&#146;s market or submarket.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
Company&#146;s 2003 annual evaluation indicated no impairment of goodwill for its
reporting units.&#160; The Company will continue to test reporting
unit goodwill for potential impairment on an annual basis in the Company&#146;s
fiscal fourth quarter, or sooner if a goodwill impairment indicator is
identified.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">As
of the date of adoption, the Company had unamortized goodwill in the amount of
$5.8 million, all of which was subject to the transition provisions of
Statement 142.&#160; Statement 142 requires
disclosure of what net income would have been in all periods presented
exclusive of amortization expense recognized in those periods related to
goodwill.&#160; Below is a reconciliation of
reported net income to adjusted net income and earnings per share (Dollars in
thousands, except earnings per share):</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Land Held for Future Development</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Real estate held for future development are sites
intended for future multifamily developments and are carried at the lower of cost or fair value.&#160;
</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Investment
In and Advances to Real Estate Joint Ventures</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s investment
in its unconsolidated real estate joint venture is recorded on the equity
method as the Company is able to exert significant influence but does not have a controlling interest in the joint
venture.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Deferred Costs and Other
Intangibles</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Deferred financing costs
are amortized over the terms of the related debt using a method which
approximates the interest method.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Derivative Financial Instruments</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In the normal course of
business, the Company uses certain derivative financial instruments to manage,
or hedge, the interest rate risk associated with the Company&#146;s variable rate
debt or as hedges in anticipation of future debt transactions to manage
well-defined interest rate risk associated with the transaction.&#160;</FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-8</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">The  Company
does not use derivative financial instruments for speculative or  trading purposes.&#160; Further,
the Company  has a policy of entering into contracts with major financial institutions
based  upon their credit rating and other factors.&#160; When viewed in conjunction with
the underlying and offsetting exposure  that the derivatives are designated to hedge, the
Company has not sustained any  material loss from those instruments nor does it
anticipate any material  adverse effect on its net income or financial position in the
future from the  use of derivatives.&#160;</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company requires that
derivative financial instruments designated as cash flow hedges be effective in
reducing the interest rate risk exposure that they are designated to
hedge.&#160; This effectiveness is essential
for qualifying for hedge accounting.&#160;
Instruments that meet the hedging criteria are formally designated as
hedging instruments at the inception of the derivative contract.&#160; The Company formally documents all
relationships between hedging instruments and hedged items, as well as its
risk-management objective and strategy for undertaking the hedge
transaction.&#160; This process includes
linking all derivatives that are designated as fair-value or cash flow hedges
to specific assets and liabilities on the balance sheet or to specific firm
commitments or forecasted transactions.&#160;
The Company also formally assesses, both at the inception of the hedging
relationship and on an ongoing basis, whether the derivatives used are highly
effective in offsetting changes in fair values or cash flows of hedged
items.&#160; When it is determined that a
derivative has ceased to be a highly effective hedge, the Company discontinues
hedge accounting prospectively.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">All of the Company&#146;s
derivative financial instruments are reported at fair value and represented on
the balance sheet, and are characterized as cash flow hedges.&#160; These transactions hedge the future cash
flows of debt transactions through interest rate swaps that convert variable
payments to fixed payments.&#160; The
unrealized gains/losses in the fair value of these hedging instruments are
reported on the balance sheet with a corresponding adjustment to accumulated
other comprehensive income, with any ineffective portion of the hedging
transactions reclassified to earnings.&#160;
During the years ended December 31, 2003, 2002 and 2001, the ineffective
portion of the hedging transactions was not significant.&#160; Within the next twelve months, the Company
expects to reclassify to earnings an estimated $100,000 of the current balance
held in accumulated other comprehensive income due to the ineffectiveness
associated with the hedging transactions.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Recent Accounting Pronouncements</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In April 2002, the FASB
issued Statement No. 145, Rescission of FASB Statements No. 4, 44, and 64,
Amendment of FASB Statement No. 13, and Technical Corrections (Statement
145).&#160; The rescission of Statement No.
4, Reporting Gains and Losses from Extinguishment of Debt and Statement No. 64,
Extinguishments of Debt made to Satisfy Sinking-Fund Requirements eliminates an
exception to general practice relating to the determination of whether certain
items should be classified as extraordinary and is effective in fiscal years
beginning after May 15, 2002, with earlier implementation encouraged.&#160; The rescission of Statement No. 44 and all
other provisions of Statement 145 are effective for fiscal years beginning
after May 15, 2002.&#160; As a result of the
adoption of Statement 145, the Company reclassified $1,444,000 and $1,189,000, representing
extraordinary gain (before minority interest adjustment) on early
extinguishment of debt for the twelve months ended December 31, 2002, and 2001, respectively, to a
component of operating income.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In December 2003, the
FASB issued FASB Interpretation No. 46 (revised December 2003), Consolidation
of Variable Interest Entities (&#147;FIN46R&#148;).&#160;
FIN46R replaces FASB Interpretation No. 46, Consolidation of Variable Interest
Entities, which was issued in January 2003, and addresses how a business
enterprise should evaluate whether it has a controlling financial interest in
an entity through means other than voting rights and how, accordingly, it
should consolidate the entity. &#160;The
Company will be required to apply FIN46R to variable interests in variable
interest entities (&#147;VIEs&#148;) created after December 31, 2003.&#160; For variable interests in VIEs created
before January 1, 2004, FIN46R will be applied beginning on January 10, 2005.&#160; For any VIEs that were created before
January 1, 2004 which must be consolidated under FIN46R, the assets,
liabilities and noncontrolling interest of the VIE would </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-9</FONT></P>


<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">initially  be
measured at their carrying values with any difference between the net amount  added to
the balance sheet and any previously recognized interest being  recognized as the
cumulative effect of an accounting change.&#160; If determining the carrying amounts is
not  practicable, fair value at the date FIN46R first applies may be used to measure  the
assets, liabilities and noncontrolling interest of the VIE.&#160; The adoption of FIN46R
is not expected to  have a material impact on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial
condition or  results of operations taken as a whole.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In April 2003, the FASB
issued Statement No. 149, Amendment of Statement No. 133, Accounting for
Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities.&#160;
Statement 149 amends and clarifies financial accounting and reporting
for derivative instruments, including certain derivative instruments embedded
in other contracts (collectively referred to as derivatives) and for hedging
activities under FASB Statement No. 133, Accounting for Derivative Instruments
and Hedging Activities.&#160; Statement 149
is effective for contracts entered into or modified after June 30, 2003.&#160; The adoption of Statement 149 had no effect
on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial condition or results of operations
taken as a whole.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">In May 2003, the FASB
issued Statement No. 150, Accounting for Certain Financial Instruments with
Characteristics of both Liabilities and Equity.&#160; Statement 150 requires issuers to classify as liabilities (or
assets in some circumstances) financial instruments within the scope of the
statement that embody unconditional obligations for the issuer.&#160; Statement 150 was effective for financial
instruments entered into or modified after May 31, 2003, and otherwise was
effective at the beginning of the first interim period beginning after June 15,
2003.&#160; The adoption of Statement 150 had
no effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial condition or results of
operations taken as a whole.</FONT></P>




<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-10</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Left Head Italic" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2"><I>Stock-Based
Compensation</I></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The
Company adopted the 1994 Restricted Stock and Stock Option Pan (the &#147;Plan&#148;) to
provide incentives to attract and retain independent directors, executive
officers and key employees.&#160; See Note 8
for further details. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company has adopted
SFAS No. 123, &#147;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation&#148;, which requires either
the (i) fair value of employee stock-based compensation plans be recorded as a
component of compensation expense in the statement of operations as of the date
of grant of awards related to such plans, or (ii) impact of such fair value on
net income and earnings per share be disclosed on a pro forma basis in a
footnote to financial statements for awards granted after December 15, 1994, if
the accounting for such awards continues to be in accordance with Accounting
Principles Board Opinion No. 25, &#147;Accounting for Stock Issued to Employees,&#148;
(&#147;APB 25&#148;).&#160; The Company will continue
such accounting under the provisions of APB 25.&#160;</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The following table
reflects the effect on net income (loss) if the fair value method of accounting
allowed under SFAS No. 123 had been used by the Company along with the
applicable assumptions utilized in the Black-Scholes option pricing model
calculation (dollars and shares in thousands, except per share data):</FONT></P>

  </TD>

  <P><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
  <TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN=BOTTOM>
  <P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=1>&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><I>Reclassification</I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Certain prior year
amounts have been reclassified to conform to 2003 presentation.&#160; The reclassifications had no effect on net
income available for common shareholders<B>.</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Real Estate Joint
Ventures</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Through August 25, 2003,
the Company owned a 33.33% interest in a joint venture (&#147;Bre/MAAC&#148;) with
Blackstone Real Estate Acquisitions, LLC (&#147;Blackstone&#148;) which was formed in
1999 when the Company sold 10 apartment communities containing 2,793 apartment
units to Bre/MAAC for $97.9 million. On </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-11</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">August  25,
2003 the Company paid $ 21.9 million in cash and assumed $ 53.2 million in  debt to
purchase Blackstone&#146;s 66.67% interest in the joint venture.&#160; This acquisition
was accounted for under the  purchase method of accounting in accordance with Statement
of Financial  Accounting Standards No. 141, <I>Business  Combinations</I>.&#160; The
purchase  accounting adjustments include an adjustment to the carrying value of the real estate
asset resulting from the previously unrecognized deferred gain on the
Company&#146;s retained interest from the original sale of the properties to  Bre/MAAC in
1999 and the recording of certain intangible assets.&#160;&#160; The operating results of
Bre/MAAC are  included in the accompanying statement of operations commencing August 25,
2003.&#160;</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The following is a
summary of 2003 operations of Bre/MAAC up until its acquisition by the
company&#160; (dollars in 000&#146;s):</FONT></P>

      <P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">)</FONT></P></TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company earns interest on its loan to CH/Realty at
an average interest rate of 9% and manages the communities for a fee of 4% of
revenues.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Investments in and
advances to real estate joint ventures consisted of the following at December
31, 2003, 2002 and 2001, respectively:&#160;
investment in Bre/MAAC: $0, $2.8 million and $3.6 million; investment in
CH/Realty:&#160; $ 7.9 million, $4.1 million
and $0; advances to Bre/MAAC: $0, $3.4 million and $3.4 million; and advances
to CH/Realty: $ 4.7 million, $4.7 million and $0.&#160; The equity in loss on real estate joint ventures for the year
ended December 31, 2003 represents the Company&#146;s share of both Bre/MAAC and
CH/Realty&#146;s net loss.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Borrowings</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company maintains a
$611 million secured credit facility with Prudential Mortgage Capital, credit-
enhanced by FNMA (the &#147;FNMA Facility&#148;).&#160;
$303 million of the FNMA Facility expires in 2004, </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-12</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">renewable  for
two successive 5-year terms, $249 million expires in 2007, and the  remaining amount
expires in 2008, both renewable for a 5-year term.&#160; The FNMA Facility provides for
both fixed  and variable rate borrowings.&#160; The  interest rate on the variable
portion renews every 90 days and is based on the  FNMA discount mortgage backed security
rate on the date of renewal, which, for  the Company, has historically approximated
three-month LIBOR less an average of  0.07%, plus a fee of 0.60% to 0.72%.&#160; Borrowings
under the FNMA Facility totaled $555.7 million at December 31,  2003, consisting of $110
million under the fixed portion at a rate of 7.179%  and the remaining $445.7 million
under the variable rate portion of the  facility. The available borrowing base capacity
at December 31, 2003 was $596.1  million. The average variable interest rate of the
facility at December 31,  2003 was 1.85%.&#160; The Company has nine  interest rate swap
agreements, totaling $275 million to effectively fix the  interest rate on a portion of
the variable rate borrowings outstanding under  the FNMA Facility at approximately 6.18%.&#160; The
swaps are highly effective and are designed as cash flow  hedges.&#160; The FNMA Facility
is subject to  certain borrowing base calculations that effectively reduce the amount
that may  be borrowed.&#160;</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Additionally, the Company
has a $55.6 million Tax-Free Bond Facility with FNMA.&#160; $42.7 million of the facility is swapped on the BMA Municipal
Swap Index.&#160; The swaps, which are highly
effective cash flow hedges, expire in 2007 and 2008 and effectively fix
interest rates at 4.3% through this period.&#160;
</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company also maintains
a $40 million secured credit facility with a group of banks led by AmSouth Bank
(the &#147;AmSouth Credit Line&#148;).&#160; The
AmSouth Credit Line bears an interest rate of LIBOR plus a spread ranging from
1.35% to 1.75% based on certain quarterly coverage calculations established by
the agreement.&#160; The spread in 2003 was
1.35%. This credit line expires in May 2005 and is subject to certain borrowing
base calculations that effectively reduce the amount that may be borrowed.&#160; At December 31, 2003, the Company had $19.0
million available to be borrowed under the AmSouth Credit Line agreement with
no outstanding balance under this facility.&#160;
$10.9 million of the facility is used for letters of credit, including
$4.8 million used to credit-enhance a tax-free bond. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company also had
outstanding at December 31, 2003 a $20 million unsecured short-term note
payable with Compass Bank at an interest rate of 1.66%, which matures in May
2004, and a $40 million promissory note with Union Planters at a variable
interest rate, (based on three month LIBOR), of 2.17% which matures in April 2009. The Company has entered
into an interest rate swap agreement with a notional amount of $25 million, a
variable leg based on three month LIBOR and a fixed leg of 4.58% which expires
in March 2009 and is designated against the Union Planters promissory
note.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">At December 31, 2003, the
Company had $205.7 million (after considering the impact of interest rate swap
agreements) variable rate debt outstanding at an average interest rate of 1.88%
and an additional $17.7 million (after considering the impact of interest rate
swap agreements) of tax-free variable rate debt outstanding at an average rate
of 1.95%; $6.8 million of which is capped under an interest rate cap agreement
at 6.00%.&#160; The interest rate on all
other debt was hedged or fixed at an average interest rate of 6.45%.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company had
approximately $336.2 million (including $55.6 million in the Tax-Free Bond
Facility with FNMA) and $446.4 million (including $46.7 million in the Tax-Free
Bond Facility with FNMA) at December 31, 2003 and 2002, respectively,
outstanding under various mortgage notes and bonds payable secured by real
estate assets. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company had
outstanding at December 31, 2002, $142 million aggregate principal amount of
6.376% bonds due in 2003 (the &#147;Bonds&#148;).&#160;
The Bonds were secured by a first priority deed of trust, security
agreement and assignment of rents and leases in 26 mortgaged properties.&#160; On March 3, 2003 these bonds were refinanced
through the FNMA Facility.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">During 2002, the Company
refinanced multiple properties and moved them under the FNMA facility.&#160; The Company also refinanced four tax-free
bonds representing $29.7 million and moved them into the </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-13</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">Tax-Free  Bond
Facility with FNMA. The Company incurred a prepayment penalty of approximately  $1.4
million related to the early extinguishment of the debt.&#160;</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">As of December 31, 2003,
the Company estimated that the weighted average interest rate on the Company&#146;s
debt was 5.4% with an average maturity of 10.6 years. </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company&#146;s indebtedness includes various
restrictive financial covenants.&#160; The
Company believes that it was in compliance with these covenants as of December 31,
2003.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair Value Disclosure of Financial
Instruments</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Cash and cash
equivalents, restricted cash, accounts payable, accrued expenses and other
liabilities and security deposits are carried at amounts which reasonably
approximate their fair value due to their short term nature.&#160; </FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">Fixed rate notes payable
at December 31, 2003 and 2002 total $385.8 million and $504.9 million,
respectively, and have an estimated fair value of $368.1 million and $470.4
million (excluding prepayment penalties) based upon interest rates available
for the issuance of debt with similar terms and remaining maturities as of
December 31, 2003 and 2002.&#160; The
carrying value of variable rate notes </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-14</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><FONT SIZE="2">payable
(excluding the effect of interest rate swap agreements) at December 31, 2003  and 2002
total $566.1 million and $298.8 million, respectively, which  reasonably approximates
their fair value because the related variable interest  rates available for the issuance
of debt with similar terms and remaining  maturities reasonably approximate market rates.&#160; The
notional amount of interest rate swap agreements at December  31, 2003 and 2002 total
$382.7 million and $159.8 million, respectively, and  have an estimated fair value of
($25.5) million and ($28.1) million based upon  interest rates available for interest
rate swaps with similar terms and  remaining maturities as of December 31, 2003 and 2002,
respectively.&#160; The fair market value of the Company&#146;s  interest rate cap
agreement with a notional amount of $6.8 million was approximately  $7,000 and $16,000 at
December 31, 2003 and 2002, respectively.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The fair value estimates
presented herein are based on information available to management as of
December 31, 2003 and 2002.&#160;These estimates are not necessarily indicative of the amounts the Company
could ultimately realize.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Commitments and Contingencies</B></FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company is not
presently subject to any material litigation nor, to the Company&#146;s knowledge,
with advice of legal counsel, is any material litigation threatened against the
Company, other than routine litigation arising in the ordinary course of
business, some of which is expected to be covered by liability insurance and
none of which is expected to have a material adverse effect on the consolidated
financial statements of the Company.</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">The Company had no
expenses related to operating leases for the year ended December 31, 2003,&#160; and $16,000, and $527,000, respectively, for
the years ended December 31, 2002, and 2001. The Company has no
commitments for the next five years under operating lease agreements outstanding
at December 31, 2003.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN"><B>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income Taxes</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">No provision for federal
income taxes has been made in the accompanying consolidated financial
statements.&#160; The Company has made an
election to be taxed as a Real Estate Investment Trust (&#147;REIT&#148;) under Sections
856 through 860 of the Code.&#160; As a REIT,
the Company generally is not subject to Federal income tax to the extent it
distributes 90% of its REIT taxable income to its shareholders and meets
certain other tests relating to the number of shareholders, types of assets and
allocable income.&#160; If the Company fails
to qualify as a REIT in any taxable year, the Company will be subject to the
Federal income tax (including any applicable alternative minimum tax) on its
taxable income at regular corporate rates.&#160;
Even though the Company qualifies for taxation as a REIT, the Company
may be subject to certain Federal, state and local taxes on its income and
property and to Federal income and excise tax on its undistributed income. </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN">F-15</FONT></P>

<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -2PX" NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<HR STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: -10PX" NOSHADE SIZE=4>
<PAGE>



<!-- MARKER FORMAT-SHEET="Para Flush" -->

income reported for financial reporting purposes primarily  because of differences in
depreciable lives, bases of certain assets and  liabilities and in the timing of
recognition of earnings upon disposition of  properties.&#160; For federal income tax
purposes, the following summarizes the taxability of cash distributions paid on  the
common shares in 2002 and 2001 and the estimated taxability for 2003:</FONT></FONT></P>
